Comment: That was gonna happen back when Snyder was working with DC. The idea was that it was gonna come out AFTER (Zack Snyder's) Justice League, but before Ben Affleck's The Batman (which he would've been the villain in). The movie was gonna be directed by Gareth Evans (the filmmaker behind The Raid movies, Apostle, and the TV series Gangs of London), with Evans and Joe Mangieanello (who Snyder casted as Deathstroke back in Justice League) writing the script. The film would've explored his relationships with William Waltergreen and Talia Al Ghul, as well as his time in the military and League of Assassins. Evans described it as along the lines of a "Korean horror film". The movie would've served as the concrete introduction to Deathstroke in the DCEU, and would build up to his villainous role in Affleck's The Batman, before then becoming a supporting character in Snyder's Justice League 2 and 3. However after the disastrous production and release of JL, WB cancelled Snyder's plans, Affleck left the DCEU and his Batman movie, and WB put Desthstroke on "indefinite hold". After a while Evans lost patience and left to work on Gangs of London and his upcoming movie Havoc (2022).

Comment:
I saw this movie recently and I have to state that it's one of the worst superhero movies ever to come out of the genre. Dwayne Johnson, whom I've liked in other films because of a certain sly sense of humor that finds its way into his roles, is here presented with a never-ending frown on his face. It barely qualifies as acting and I genuinely thought of him as an actor. Admittedly, he's no Meryl Streep but he had his moments. In "Black Adam", he's got one single expression throughout this film and it rarely varies: Rock by name, rock by nature, I guess. 

The film itself is almost nonstop violence while at the same time lauding violence as the question AND the solution. The boy Amon relishes the idea of a hero who can kill his enemies with superhuman speed and strength, as if to him "hero" is synonymous with "guard dog". Amon's people cheer when Teth Adam demolishes the opposition, not seeming to care that his vicious actions cause massive property damage and potential loss of civilian life. Compare that with "Captain America: Civil War" where some of The Avengers were appalled with the people they'd accidentally killed while taking down members of HYDRA. There is a scene where Teth Adam is fighting Hawkman in a woman's apartment and they practically demolish the place, slamming through the walls, tearing up the furniture and wrecking the possessions! Why does nobody yell at them to stop it or to take it outside, at least? Oh, yeah. That love of  violence again.

In 1978, we got a Superman who ascribed himself as a friend and you could believe it. His was a humble nature that saw himself as being on the same side of law enforcement, who took time to stop burglars AND pull a kitten out of tree. (The only way I could see Deadpool interacting with a cat is if he sh** in its litterbox.) Our current Superman is a red-eyed rage-aholic who goes about snapping people's necks. Who the heck is that guy?!

It states something awful about a culture where children laud imaginary heroes because of their capacity for brutal action rather than peaceable resolutions. Ours is not a culture that adores philosophers, scholars, teachers, sages, doctors, firemen or any other people who bring amicable solutions to social and political problems. Are there people out there who look up to Mahatma Gandhi or Martin Luther King, Jr.? If there are, we don't hear from them. Instead, we've got people who loudly drool over zombies, vampires and werewolves (you know, monsters that KILL human beings) as fictional love partners and admire unreal heroes like Deadpool, Punisher, Batman and other beings who bring justice by curb-stomping their enemies into the ground. 


If we're going to continue making superhero films, we've got to do better. Films like "Black Adam" are just embarrassing.

@filips2146  No. Doesn't fit at all with a god-like being that comes from a northern Africa/Southern Europe fictional country in times of ancient Egypt. 

Music in a movie has to remind you and make you think about the themes or the point of the movie itself. In this case it could be the main character himself. But this music choice doesn't get that at all.

 Even if it was an original song with lyrics that were explicitly about Black Adam, it's an issue with the genre itself. It just has nothing that resonates with the character in a more meaningful way.


 And just because you think the song by itself is good, it still doesn't mean it fits well. And it really doesn't. Comment:
Low and behold, the movie is 1 year old!!!

My most hyped up movie of the fall
Not as bad as many are making it 
Violent but funny, exciting, opens more of the DCEU
Dwayne Johnson has a lot of charisma and Sarah Shahi and especially Pierce Brosnan as Dr. Fate 
The team called the Justice Society of America is fun even if not all the members are fleshed out 
Plus the action scenes are amazing and the plot is easy to follow despite a lot of slo mo and exposition next to the flashbacks 
Great cameo too from a familiar actor from a previous film 
A very weak villain though as you'd expect 
Says a lot about having a champion in a 3rd world country as far as representation, diplomacy, heroism, choosing to be a destroyer or savior, being worthy of god like powers or not, being up to fate to decide our outcome 
15 years of Johnson playing this character was worth the wait, this is one of my favorite DC comic book characters now

Comment: When you see 'Black Adam' for the 2nd time, and it really does take more than one screening to have a grasp of story, emotions, and where it fits in the collective fantasy worlds, so you can have an informed opinion. Many things I didn't see the first time on the plane, with the little screen staring back at me. Now. At home. Big computer screen and I can see all the things I missed. I can see why many actors are into this idea of how movies are weaker than they used to be. They're talking about themselves. You know? Movies are getting astronomically more skilled at making impossible realities, come true. Johnson is not a spring chicken, but he pulls a LOT of weight as a fantasy, comic book hero, on screen. And THAT will give an actor confidence. Brosnan and Hodge were really packing it, in 'Black Adam.' Everything I heard, about 'BA' made me predict a horrible movie, and really happy I was 100 percent off the mark. THIS is an awesome movie. Johnson and Cavill no longer planning any more movies is too bad. But. You can go really far with a dude like Hodge. He's basically a foundation to build on, if DC wants a quick way to their version of Marvel's 'End Game.' Whoever came up with this 'version' of Hawkman is WAY beyond me. Like light years beyond me. And I'm really into comic book worlds. Great job.

Comment: So, on May 4th, 2023, I finally saw this movie.  I was sitting on a plane on my way to Egypt for my 50th birthday.  I know we are 1 year and a few days apart in this life.  Once I arrived in Egypt, I realized that this movie hit closer to home than ever.  Hades, (oh yeah, they do not call it that anymore) Egypt, looks nothing like how I last saw it.  Back during the time of Moses and Ramses and well You Dwayne or should I say Osiris.  My deal and the ideology behind the pyramids and such as well as you & Moses Grandfather God have kept me away from my own nation for many Thousands if not hundreds of thousands of years.  I thought immediately of this movie as I walked around town and such.  I did get some police officers to change something after I had a run in with them.  A small step in police reform, since this is the nation where that was created it was befitting that I get them to make a adjustment.  Anyway Mr. Johnson happy belated birthday.

Comment:
Can we take a moment to appreciate all the symbolism of the oppression of Palestine and it’s people?

First the scene with Mo Amer in a car with foreigners having a checkpoint and running an obviously frivolous check of his identity IN HIS OWN COUNTRY. Remember that Amer is Palestinian.

Johnson plays the role of Black Adam. Amon tells Black Adam that ever since his death, his country has been subjected to numerous invaders and oppression. That his people have been waiting for the return of Black Adam.

In Biblical terms, Jesus is referred to as The New Adam. He is considered the Savior (in Christian culture) who will have a second coming (both in Christian and Islamic cultures). Palestine has been a country invaded by the Greeks, Romans, etc and its people have been subjected to imperialism and oppression. Today, by the Israeli regime, a self-imposed state (not to be confused with the religious or ethnic Jews, though many Jews do live there) which denies Palestinian people freedom, peace, and equal treatment as citizens of the land.

Awesome symbolism!

Comment: The only good thing about this super hero movie is The Rock who plays his character perfectly. Everything else is pretty much over produced trash. The CGI is clunky and poorly done in parts, and that's unforgivable in a modern movie with an approx 200 million dollar budget. The dialogue ranges from witty  to generic predictable super hero ra ra nonsense. The plot is without any original ideas, and the super heroes sent to battle Adam lame all around. The actors themselves all do a decent job with what they are given (fun to see Pierce Brosnan as Dr. Fate) but it can't save this movie. The Superman cameo at the end was a missed opportunity but now that  Cavill is no longer Superman, they will not be able to follow up with the set up for a battle between them. C-

Comment: Loved the seriousness of the Rock. Such an underrated actor. This movie did not take the time to develop the other characters except for the clear crushes of our young heroes. Great chemistry.The visuals were amazing! I never read the comic book so have no idea who they all are. Still don't after watching the movie. I understood who Black Adam was but not the other characters. The one thing I could NOT stand is the soundtrack. Too loud in many places where it should have been soft. What I mean is, sequences that had no REAL action, just characters talking, should not be accompanied by an  'action' soundtrack, especially one heavy with a horn section. A Horn section is serious business and should be saved for a climatic scene. Very bad choice. Good lord, it was distracting. Sound tracks are meant to control the viewer's emotions and they totally missed the mark. Gone are the years of John Williams and Danny Elfman of my time. However,  this was an improvement over Wonder Woman 1984. The only part I enjoyed of that movie is Gail Gadot, I can't even imagine another actress doing Wonder Woman ever again, she's perfect. Dear WB, give Gadot a better script!!
